I joined the party since 2007. At the time, Djibouti was ruled by its authoritarian president, Ismail Omar Guelleh (IOG). The opposition, with two or three smaller parties joined together, plus a few politicians called themselves Viberant Party. It formed the nucleus of opposition to the regime. Though Viberant Party is not strong but it developed and diversified into the Democratic Peoples’ Unity Party (PUD), which in turn grew into a party of its own.

In Djibouti, people desire change but not enmity. Waging a campaign for change is not good for the country in such a tense environment. Political discourse is a hazard to Djibouti. Presidents acquire power through ballot paper. But the choice is limited and voters who are independent and raised doubts about those reserved silence and threats that is to keeping party and its members in the limelight. A sense of national unity is witnessed in all over Djibouti. Our only commitment is to strengthen our ties with others.

The VIPERANT party has assigned me as High Commissioner to Crossover in-charge of supporting refugees as well as Eritrean homeless people and illegal immigrants in and outside Djibouti. This is a reasonable way to unite people of all walks of life rather than tolerate obsolete authority and hide political groupings
